{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca463cfe-98a7-4757-bf79-133c53357e73","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test ID generation strategy** from `DisplayName` to `FullyQualifiedName` by default. Azure DevOps tracks tests by ID, so every test looks new.\n\n**Fix:** Add a `.runsettings` file to restore the old behavior:\n\n```xml\n<RunSettings>\n  <MSTest>\n    <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n  </MSTest>\n</RunSettings>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v3, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` was secretly the context of the *first test to execute*, so `TestName` happened to work. In v4, it's now a proper **class-level context** — `TestName` is not available and throws.\n\n**Fix for your code:** Remove the `TestName` access since `[ClassInitialize]` runs once per class, not per test:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is no longer available here in v4.\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName if you need the class name.\n}\n```\n\nIf you truly need per-test setup, move that logic to `[TestInitialize]` where `TestContext.TestName` is still valid.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | What changed |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` type matching** | Stricter type coercion — `[DataRow(1)]` no longer auto-converts to `long` params. Match types exactly. |\n| **Cleanup timing** | `[ClassCleanup]` now defaults to `EndOfClass` (was `EndOfAssembly`). If cleanup order matters, set `[ClassCleanup(ClassCleanupBehavior.EndOfAssembly)]` explicitly. |\n| **Assertions** | `Assert.AreEqual` on floating-point uses a stricter default tolerance. If you had borderline float tests, they may now fail. |\n| **Parallel execution** | The default parallelism scope changed. If you see new race conditions, verify your `[Parallelize]` attribute or `.runsettings`. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Writing to `TestContext.Properties` in fixture methods may now throw. Use it as read-only or switch to instance fields. |\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to apply the fix to your `SetupTests.cs` or generate a `.runsettings` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88fd362f-37f5-41df-b1a5-fc6700d98bb2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the user's situation. Let me address the known MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Test IDs changed** — MSTest v4 changed test IDs to be fully qualified, which breaks test history in Azure DevOps and other CI systems.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in ClassInitialize** — In MSTest v4, `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` no longer has `TestName` populated (it's a class-level context, not tied to a specific test), so accessing it throws or returns null.\n\n3. **Other breaking changes** to watch out for.\n\nLet me provide a thorough answer based on my knowledge of MSTest v4 changes.\n\n\nThe fully qualified test ID change can be mitigated by configuring the `TestIdGenerationStrategy` in the `.runsettings` file to preserve the old naming convention. The `TestContext` issue in `[ClassInitialize]` is intentional—since class initialization runs once for the entire class rather than per test, there's no single test name to provide, so code relying on that needs to be refactored to avoid accessing `TestName` in that context.\n\nBeyond these two main issues, there are several other compatibility concerns: `[DataRow]` attributes now enforce stricter type matching, assembly and class cleanup methods have different timing behavior, `TestContext.Properties` is read-only by default, and parallel execution settings may differ from previous versions.","outputTokens":1057,"requestId":"A04D:197E70:1C2B198:2053A6C:69FEA3FC"},"id":"9f3c5a66-2029-4af2-bb65-ecc944705baa","timestamp":"2026-05-09T03:03:47.244Z","parentId":"d38c222b-0317-4ec6-8357-76dc193dc0b0"}
